description:
Runner module directly calls http_client.execute_request(), making it impossible to unit test orchestration logic without real HTTP. Extract a BehaviorExecutor type that can be injected, allowing tests to mock HTTP responses.

Current (runner.gleam:225):
  case http_client.execute_request(config, rb.behavior.request, ctx) { ... }

Target:
  pub type BehaviorExecutor {
    BehaviorExecutor(execute: fn(Config, Request, Context) -> Result(ExecutionResult, ExecutionError))
  }

  pub fn run_spec_with_executor(spec, target_url, options, executor) -> SpecResult

This enables tests like:
  let mock = BehaviorExecutor(fn(_, req, _) { Ok(ExecutionResult(status: 200, ...)) })
  runner.run_spec_with_executor(spec, "", options, mock)

Loader module mixes UI concerns (spinner) with file loading logic. This makes it impossible to test CUE parsing without seeing spinner output. Extract pure business logic into testable functions.

Current (loader.gleam:38-57):
  fn load_and_parse(path: String) -> Result(Spec, LoadError) {
    let sp = spinner.new(...) |> spinner.start  // UI mixed in!
    case validate_cue(path) { ... }
  }

Target:
  // Pure business logic - TESTABLE
  fn load_and_parse_impl(path: String) -> Result(Spec, LoadError) {
    use _ <- result.try(validate_cue(path))
    export_and_parse(path)
  }

  // Public API with UI
  pub fn load_spec(path: String) -> Result(Spec, LoadError) { ... with spinner ... }

  // Quiet API for testing/automation  
  pub fn load_spec_quiet(path: String) -> Result(Spec, LoadError) { ... no spinner ... }

RunOptions uses a boolean 'verbose' flag which is less expressive than a union type. This makes it harder to add future output levels (quiet, debug) and less self-documenting.

Current (runner.gleam:20-26):
  pub type RunOptions {
    RunOptions(
      feature_filter: Option(String),
      behavior_filter: Option(String),
      verbose: Bool,  // What does True/False mean?
    )
  }

Target:
  pub type OutputLevel {
    Quiet
    Normal  
    Verbose
  }

  pub type RunOptions {
    RunOptions(
      feature_filter: Option(String),
      behavior_filter: Option(String),
      output_level: OutputLevel,
    )
  }

Benefits: More expressive, easier to extend with Debug/Silent, pattern matching is self-documenting.
